"use `entire disable --uninstall` to remove agents\n\nthis removes all agents, right? can we add `--agent` here?\n\n---\n\nI feel this is not great, now `disable` makes uninstall an agent also it's called diasble :thinking:\n\n---\n\nlet's do second, and advertise it\n\n---\n\nMedium Severity\n\nWhen a user runs entire disable (writes enabled: false to settings.local.json) and then entire enable --project, runEnable writes enabled: true to settings.json but doesn't clear the enabled: false in settings.local.json. Because settings.Load merges both files with local overriding project, the effective state remains disabled. The user sees \"Entire is now enabled.\" but IsEnabled() still returns false.\n\n---\n\ncan you add a test for this\n\n---\n\nrunSetupFlow always calls runEnableInteractive with an empty EnableOptions{}. As a result, flags provided to entire enable / entire configure on first-time setup (e.g. --local/--project, --skip-push-sessions, --telemetry=false, --absolute-git-hook-path, etc.) are ignored when the repo is fresh. Consider passing the caller’s EnableOptions into runSetupFlow (e.g. runSetupFlow(ctx, w, opts)) and forwarding it to runEnableInteractive so initial setup honors the CLI flags.\n\n---\n\nIn entire configure --agent ... mode, the command calls agent.Get(...) without first running external.DiscoverAndRegister(ctx). This means external agent plugins (entire-agent-* binaries) won’t be found even when external_agents is enabled, and the command will incorrectly report “Unknown agent”. Recommend calling external.DiscoverAndRegister(ctx) before checking/using --agent (and before listing agents).\n\n---\n\ncan you take a look at the comments on the PR? we addressed some here already"